{"status":"OK","data":{"id":57733,"identifier":"DVN/8QFXOE","persistentUrl":"https://doi.org/10.7910/DVN/8QFXOE","protocol":"doi","authority":"10.7910","publisher":"Harvard Dataverse","publicationDate":"2008-12-18","storageIdentifier":"s3://dvn-cloud:1902.1/11305","latestVersion":{"id":78306,"storageIdentifier":"s3://dvn-cloud:1902.1/11305","versionNumber":1,"versionMinorNumber":1,"versionState":"RELEASED","distributionDate":"2008","productionDate":"Production Date","lastUpdateTime":"2015-11-23T21:08:38Z","releaseTime":"2015-11-23T21:08:38Z","createTime":"2015-11-23T21:02:05Z","license":"NONE","termsOfUse":"<h1> IFPRI  DATAVERSE TERMS OF USE </h1> By using this website and any of the materials made available through it, you agree to abide by the Terms of Use of IFPRI Dataverse. The datasets and documents in this study are licensed under a <a rel=\"license\" href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/\">Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 3.0 Unported License</a> <a rel=\"license\" href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/\"></a>   <a rel=\"license\" href=\"http://creativecommons.o\r\nrg/licenses/by-nc/3.0/\"><img alt=\"Creative Commons License\" style=\"border-width:0\" src=\"http://i.creativecommons.org/l/by-nc/3.0/80x15.png\" /></a><br />","metadataBlocks":{"citation":{"displayName":"Citation Metadata","fields":[{"typeName":"title","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"A 1991 Social Accounting Matrix (SAM) For Zimbabwe"},{"typeName":"author","multiple":true,"typeClass":"compound","value":[{"authorName":{"typeName":"authorName","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"Marcelle Thomas"},"authorAffiliation":{"typeName":"authorAffiliation","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"International Food Policy Research Institute (IFPRI)"}},{"authorName":{"typeName":"authorName","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"Romeo M. Bautista"},"authorAffiliation":{"typeName":"authorAffiliation","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"International Food Policy Research Institute (IFPRI)"}}]},{"typeName":"datasetContact","multiple":true,"typeClass":"compound","value":[{"datasetContactName":{"typeName":"datasetContactName","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"IFPRI-DATA"},"datasetContactAffiliation":{"typeName":"datasetContactAffiliation","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"International Food Policy Research Institute (IFPRI)"},"datasetContactEmail":{"typeName":"datasetContactEmail","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"IFPRI-Data@cgiar.org"}}]},{"typeName":"dsDescription","multiple":true,"typeClass":"compound","value":[{"dsDescriptionValue":{"typeName":"dsDescriptionValue","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"The 1991 Social Accounting Matrix (SAM) for Zimbabwe that we document in this paper is intended to provide benchmark data for economy-wide analysis under the MERRISA Project. Its construction is based on a three-step process: (1) building a\r\nmacro SAM that presents the aggregative features of the Zimbabwean economy and serves as a control matrix for the micro SAM; (2) disaggregation into a complete but unbalanced micro SAM; and (3) balancing the disaggregated and complete micro SAM using the cross-entropy approach. The macro SAM entries are based on aggregates from a recent, significant revision of the Zimbabwe national accounts for 1991. The structure of the micro SAM is a disaggregated version of the macro SAM. The outcome is an\r\n88 by 88 matrix that includes 36 activities, 27 commodities, 9 factors of production (4 labor , 3 capital, and 2 land categories), 5 households groups, and one account each for enterprises, government, investment/saving, and rest-of-the-world. Among the significant features of the Zimbabwean economy that are explicitly taken into account in the SAM structure are\r\nthe importance of agriculture, the distinction between smallholder and large-scale commercial farms, home consumption by smallholder farm households, and the large marketing margins that reflect inefficiencies in trade and transport infrastructure."}}]},{"typeName":"subject","multiple":true,"typeClass":"controlledVocabulary","value":["Arts and Humanities","Social Sciences"]},{"typeName":"keyword","multiple":true,"typeClass":"compound","value":[{"keywordValue":{"typeName":"keywordValue","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"social accounting matrix"},"keywordVocabulary":{"typeName":"keywordVocabulary","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"STW Thesaurus for Economics"},"keywordVocabularyURI":{"typeName":"keywordVocabularyURI","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"http://zbw.eu/stw/descriptor/19237-2"}},{"keywordValue":{"typeName":"keywordValue","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"SAM"}},{"keywordValue":{"typeName":"keywordValue","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"Zimbabwe"},"keywordVocabulary":{"typeName":"keywordVocabulary","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"AGROVOC"},"keywordVocabularyURI":{"typeName":"keywordVocabularyURI","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"http://aims.fao.org/aos/agrovoc/c_8516"}},{"keywordValue":{"typeName":"keywordValue","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"Southern Africa"},"keywordVocabulary":{"typeName":"keywordVocabulary","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"AGROVOC"},"keywordVocabularyURI":{"typeName":"keywordVocabularyURI","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"http://aims.fao.org/aos/agrovoc/c_7265"}},{"keywordValue":{"typeName":"keywordValue","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"Africa South of Sahara"},"keywordVocabulary":{"typeName":"keywordVocabulary","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"AGROVOC"},"keywordVocabularyURI":{"typeName":"keywordVocabularyURI","multiple":false,"typeClass":"primitive","value":"http://aims.fao.org/aos/agrovoc/c_166"}},{"keywordValue":{"typeName":"keywordValue","mult